@node "Intro" "Introduction"
Amiga Password Protection System or APPS is a multi-user password system.

It uses a user-file system that stores the information for each user in a file.

APPS allows the user to have thier own start up sequence and (in the case of the pro version) their own hard drive partition.

APPS also comes with some eatra utilties not least of which is APPSetup. This is the setup program for APPS which sets up the user id andd passwords. It uses a similar interface as APPS so users of apps will feel at home.

APPS come in two versions. Standard and Pro version. The programs are almost identical except the Pro version allow the user to setup their own partition as well as their own startup-sequence.

I hope you find using APPS useful, and watch out for future releases and updates.
@endnode

@node "Req" "Requirements"
 APPS requires the following:

 Kickstart 2.04+
 About 512k of Mem.

 Not my eh!.

 APPS and APPSetup were written on the following setup.

 Amiga 1200, Magnum 25mhz 68040, 8mb Fast RAM, Seagate 520Mb Hard drive, EIDE 8x CD-ROM DRIVE

 written using Blitz Basic 2.1
@endnode

@node "Usage" "Usage"

 Installing apps is pretty simple.

 You can either use the supplied installer program(does not use commodore installer yet) or do it
 manually.

 Pro version users should check the PRO Version DOC.

 Stanadard version users continue reading.

 To install APPS manually follow these steps by steps instructions.

 1. Make a directory called logonfiles in your sys: directory.

 2. Copy the apps to the c: directory

 3. copy the files APPSetup and APPSetup.info to the prefs draw of your sys: device.

 4. copy all files in the images draw to the s: directory.

 5. rename your s:startup-sequence as s:startup-sequence2 or any name of your choice. but remember
    what you called it.

 6. Type ed s:startup-sequence into a shell window and type the following:

                Setpatch >NIL:
                Assign >NIL: ENV: RAM:
                run >NIL: c:apps
                endcli

    the hit esc x to save.  (DO NOT RESET! DO NOT RESET!)

 7. Run APPSetup.

    Type in a user id and password.

    Fill in the other details (name, aka).

    Stanadard users don't have to enter anything into the mount device string as it is not
    used by APPS standard any way.

    When you get to startup-sequence type in s:startup-sequence2 or what ever you called yours

    The hit save.

 8. Reset and if all has been followed correctly the apps program will boot up and all you have to do
    is type in your user id and password.

    It doesn't matter about case because in apps everything is converted to lower-case anyway.
@endnode

@node "Bugs" "Bugs"

  There are only a few bugs in apps which will hopefully be sorted with version 3.2

  The bugs that i have found are as follows.

  1. After program has been run mouse stays on amigados screen until mouse button is clicked

  2. Program requests the ENV: directory when run menaing that the amigados screen is opened rather
     than the usual and better black screen.

  3. The password string is not disguised so the password is still visible to preying eyes.

  4. When using more than 4 colours the menus go all pear shaped in the colour department.  This
     can be fixed using magic menus but this only really works with APPSetup. Could be a bug in Blitz
@endnode

